{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KsnPhWdDRxek11iFrUiGHF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the setup. There are two Ingress resources:\n1. `rate-api` - handles `/api` path, no rate limiting currently\n2. `rate-health` - handles `/health` path, should remain unlimited\n\nThe ingress-nginx controller has 3 replicas.\n\nFor rate limiting with ingress-nginx, I need to add annotations to the `rate-api` ingress. The key annotations are:\n- `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-rps` - limits requests per second per IP\n- `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-connections` - limits connections per IP\n\nSince each replica maintains its own rate limiting state independently, having 3 replicas means the effective limit multiplies across them. To achieve a true ~1 RPS limit across all replicas, I'd need to set each replica to roughly 0.33 RPS, though the annotation doesn't directly support fractional values in that way.\n\nI'm considering different approaches: setting `limit-rps: 1` per replica would allow up to 3 RPS total if requests distribute evenly, but the requirement is specifically for approximately 1 RPS. The \"replica hard\" aspect of the test suggests I need to account for how multiple replicas affect the actual rate limiting behavior from the client's perspective. replica would receive about 0.67 RPS. Looking at the test, it sends 10 requests over 5 seconds (2 RPS total), expecting some to hit rate limits. So I need to set the limit low enough that this traffic gets throttled across the replicas. 1 request per second with burst capacity, so at 0.67 RPS per replica most requests would pass through. With `limit-rpm: 1` it becomes much stricter—only 1 request per minute per replica, which would definitely trigger rejections. The real challenge here is that nginx rate limiting uses a token bucket algorithm and each replica enforces limits independently, so without shared state like Redis, there's no way to coordinate rate limits across the cluster—each replica just applies its own rules to incoming traffic. default it allows a burst of 5 times the limit, so with `limit-rps: 1` I'd get a burst of 5 requests before hitting 429. With 3 replicas each getting ~0.67 RPS from a 2 RPS stream, the rate limit might not trigger consistently. The most reliable approach is to set both `limit-rps` and `limit-rpm` to very low values and disable the burst multiplier entirely. ~0.67 RPS per replica, so the burst would handle the initial requests but then rate limiting kicks in. I need to reconsider what the test actually expects—it just needs some requests to return 429 or 503, not all of them. Since I have 3 replicas, setting `limit-rps: 1` per replica gives an effective 3 RPS total, which is higher than the test's 2 RPS, so nothing would get rejected. I need to lower the per-replica limit to achieve roughly 1 RPS effective across all replicas. With round-robin load balancing across three replicas, consecutive requests would hit different replicas spaced 1.5 seconds apart, so a 1 RPS limit with no burst should allow them through without rejections. But if the load balancing isn't perfectly round-robin, some requests might hit the same replica within the 1-second window and get rejected. is 20 RPM, each replica would reject requests exceeding that rate. With 3 replicas handling 2 RPS total traffic, the per-replica load would exceed the limit and trigger rejections. This approach using `limit-rpm` with a conservative per-replica threshold should achieve the desired rate limiting behavior. So the burst calculation depends on whether we're using RPM or RPS limits. For RPM-based limits, the burst gets computed as `limit-rpm * limit-burst-multiplier / 60`, which with the default multiplier of 5 gives us a pretty small burst window. Let me trace through what the actual ingress-nginx controller does when generating the NGINX config from these annotations.\n\nThe key realization is that with `limit-rps: 1` and the default burst multiplier of 5, the first 5 requests pass immediately, then it enforces 1 request per second. In my test with 10 total requests across 3 replicas, each replica gets roughly 3 requests, so they all pass through the burst allowance. To actually see failures, I need to either reduce the burst multiplier to 1 or set a rate low enough that even distributed across replicas, some requests exceed the limit.\n\nWith `limit-rpm: 10` and burst multiplier 1, the rate becomes 1 request every 6 seconds per replica, which should be strict enough to trigger rejections when requests arrive faster than that interval. ation would be to set `limit-rpm: 20` with `limit-burst-multiplier: 1`, giving each replica roughly 1 request every 3 seconds with a burst of 1, which across 3 replicas distributes to approximately 1 RPS total. Testing this with round-robin distribution at 2 RPS (requests every 0.5 seconds) shows the first request passes on each replica before hitting the rate limit.\n\nNow I'm verifying the NGINX burst calculation in ingress-nginx to make sure `limit-burst-multiplier: 1` is actually valid and how it translates to the underlying `limit_req_zone` configuration. With `limit-burst-multiplier: 1`, the burst value calculates to 1, so NGINX generates a config allowing 1 extra request to be served immediately before rejecting excess requests with a 429 status. This means the effective rate is 20 requests per minute (one every 3 seconds) with a single request allowed to burst ahead without queueing.\n\nWhen a client sends requests at 2 RPS to a single replica, the first request uses the burst token and passes, but subsequent requests arrive before the next token accumulates (which takes 3 seconds), so they get rejected. However, with round-robin distribution across 3 replicas, each replica receives requests spaced further apart—roughly every 1.5 seconds—which allows some requests to pass as tokens regenerate on each replica independently. Let me trace through the token bucket refills for each replica more carefully. R1 passes at t=0 and t=3.0, getting rejected at t=1.5 and t=4.5. For R2, it passes at t=0.5, then I need to check if the token refills in time for the request at t=3.5—since the last pass was at t=0.5, three seconds later would be t=3.5, so that request should pass. R3 follows a similar pattern with its own timing.\n\nCounting up the results: R1 gets 2 passes and 2 rejections, R2 gets 2 passes and 1 rejection, and R3 gets 2 passes and 1 rejection, giving me 6 total passes and 4 total rejections.\n\nSo 4 out of 10 requests would hit the 429 limit, which satisfies the requirement of some requests being rejected while maintaining an overall rate of about 1.2 RPS. I think `limit-rpm: 20` with `limit-burst-multiplier: 1` is the right configuration.\n\nLet me verify that ingress-nginx actually supports the `limit-burst-multiplier` annotation—yes, it does, with a default value of 5. I should also check how `nodelay` works in this context. When `limit-rps` or `limit-rpm` is configured, the generated nginx config uses `limit_req` with a burst parameter and the `nodelay` flag, which means requests within the burst are processed immediately rather than being queued.\n\nThe default status code for rate limiting in ingress-nginx is 503, but I can set it to 429 if needed using the `limit-status-code` annotation. Since the test accepts either status code, I don't need to worry about that.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the approach with `limit-rps: 1` per replica. The test sends 10 requests at 2 RPS total, which means each replica in a round-robin setup receives about 0.67 RPS. To ensure some requests fail, I need each replica's limit to be below that rate. Options like `limit-rpm: 20` (0.333 RPS) would definitely cause some failures.\n\nLooking at the burst calculation with `limit-rpm: 20` and the default burst multiplier of 5, the burst works out to 1 request, which aligns with my earlier analysis. So I probably don't need to adjust the burst multiplier separately.\n\nNow examining `limit-rps: 1` with a burst of 1 across 3 replicas using round-robin distribution—each replica would receive requests roughly every 1.5 seconds, which the rate limit should accommodate.\n\nSo `limit-rps: 1` won't suffice here. I need to set `limit-rpm: 20` on the rate-api ingress, and I should verify whether ingress-nginx applies rate limiting per replica or globally across all replicas.\n\nEach replica maintains its own rate limiting zone without sharing state, which means clients get rate limited individually per replica rather than across the entire service. With `limit-rpm: 20` distributing requests round-robin across replicas, I'd expect roughly 4 rejections per 10 requests.\n\nMy approach: add the `limit-rpm: 20` annotation to the rate-api ingress and leave the rate-health ingress as is. I'm also considering whether to set `limit-rps` alongside `limit-rpm`, though I need to check how ingress-nginx handles both annotations being set simultaneously. So the burst calculation confirms my analysis either way—with 20 RPM I get a burst of 1, which means roughly 4 out of 10 requests hit the rate limit across the 3 replicas, giving an effective throughput of about 1 RPS. Now I'm considering whether there are other approaches like using Kubernetes ConfigMaps or connection limits to achieve better results.\n\nThe real solution is to annotate the `rate-api` ingress directly with the `limit-rpm: 20` setting, and I should leave the `rate-api-alt-hard` ingress untouched since it's for a different host. Let me think through whether there are any other edge cases I'm missing. to same replica) = 1/3, so there's a decent chance of back-to-back requests hitting the same instance and triggering the rate limit. This randomized distribution actually strengthens the test's ability to demonstrate rate limiting in action.\n\nLet me just go with 20 RPM and run the test—the probability analysis suggests it should work as intended.\n\nWait, I need to reconsider how `limit_req` with `nodelay` actually behaves. With `burst=1 nodelay`, the first request consumes the burst slot and passes immediately, then subsequent requests are rejected until the rate window allows another request through.\n\nLooking at the internal mechanics: NGINX tracks \"excess\" debt for each IP in milliseconds. When a request arrives, it calculates whether the accumulated excess exceeds the burst threshold. With `nodelay`, requests are served immediately if they fit within the burst, but the excess counter increases accordingly. If excess exceeds the burst delay, the request gets rejected with a 429. the algorithm tracks excess requests relative to the rate limit, where each incoming request increments the excess counter and elapsed time decrements it. If the excess exceeds the burst threshold, the request gets rejected with a 429 response. Let me trace through a concrete example to verify how this plays out. 666 - 0.5/3) + 1 = 2.499 + 1 = 3.499 > 2 → REJECT\n\nWith round-robin distribution across 3 replicas, requests hit each replica every 1.5 seconds instead. The first request to R1 is allowed with excess=1, the fourth request at 1.5s gets excess=1.5 and passes, and by the seventh request at 3s the excess reaches 2.0 while continuing to decay.\n\nAt 4.5 seconds, the tenth request would push excess to 2.5, exceeding the limit and getting rejected. Checking the same pattern for R2 and R3, the second and fifth requests are allowed, and by the eighth request at 3.5 seconds the excess reaches exactly 2.0.\n\nSo with perfect round-robin distribution, only one request gets rejected out of ten. That's cutting it close. Let me try tightening the limit to 10 requests per minute instead. Continuing through the round-robin distribution, R1 rejects requests 7 and 10 once the excess capacity exceeds the limit, while R2 and R3 follow the same pattern—allowing the first two requests but rejecting the third. This gives us 6 total passes and 4 rejections across all three runners, resulting in a 40% rejection rate and an effective throughput of 1.2 requests per second with the 10 RPM limit.\n\nWith random distribution via iptables, the results would fluctuate, but using `limit-rpm: 10` ensures consistent rejections. I'm reconsidering whether this actually meets the \"approximately 1 request per second\" requirement—with three independent replicas each enforcing 10 RPM, that's 0.167 RPS per replica, but under round-robin distribution each replica sees 0.67 RPS, so excess requests do get rejected as intended. The effective rate that actually passes through is what matters here.\n\nActually, the test just needs some rejections to work—even one rejection out of ten would be sufficient. I'm leaning toward `limit-rpm: 20` since it produces at least one rejection and gets closer to the 1 RPS target, though I should keep in mind that with iptables NAT rules, the load distribution is statistically random rather than perfectly round-robin, so some replicas might receive more traffic than others with only 10 requests.\n\nGiven this uncertainty, I'm going to be more conservative and use `limit-rpm: 15` instead. This gives a rate of one request per 4 seconds with a burst capacity of 1, and even with round-robin distribution across replicas, the token bucket should accumulate enough excess to trigger rejections by the third request.\n\nLooking at how requests would distribute across three replicas with this setting, I'd expect around 6 requests to pass and 4 to be rejected, which is similar to what I calculated for 10 RPM. Since the task just needs some 429 responses for excess requests without specifying an exact number, `limit-rpm: 20` should work fine. Let me check what the alternative hard rate limit configuration uses—it might give me a clue about what value to target.\n\nI'll apply the annotation with `limit-rpm: 20` and run the test, adjusting if needed. The key thing to remember is that ingress-nginx's `limit-rpm` annotation creates rate limiting per IP address, so the limit applies to each client separately. The standard ingress-nginx approach with `limit-rpm` is the way to go here, even though it's per-replica. I'll set `limit-rpm: 20` which gives roughly 0.333 RPS per replica, and with 3 replicas that approximates the 1 RPS target the task is looking for. Let me also explore `limit-rps: 1` with `limit-burst-multiplier: 1` to see if that provides better control across the distributed setup. I need to figure out what load balancing mode the cluster actually uses—Kind typically defaults to iptables rather than IPVS. Since I'm not certain, I should go with the safer option: `limit-rpm: 20` works reliably across both random and round-robin balancing scenarios. Let me double-check my analysis for the round-robin case with that rate limit.\n\nNow I'm working through the exact NGINX rate limiting algorithm to verify how the excess request counter behaves with a 20 requests-per-minute limit. Let me work through a concrete example to see how this plays out in practice. With a 20 RPM limit (about 0.333 RPS per replica) and a burst of 1, if the test sends requests at 2 RPS across 3 replicas, each replica receives roughly 0.67 RPS—which exceeds the limit and will trigger rejections. The exact count depends on the load balancing pattern and NGINX's precise formula, but the outcome is clear: some requests will be rejected.\n\nSo my plan is to annotate the rate-api service with the 20 RPM limit and a burst multiplier of 1, then run the test to verify we get a mix of 200s and 429s. If rejections are too sparse, I can lower the RPM further. I need to double-check the correct annotation name for setting the HTTP status code on rate-limit responses. The ingress controller Service load balances across the replicas, so I need to make sure the rate limiting works consistently. Let me outline my approach: first check if there's already a ref