ed time and adding 1000 units for the current request, then rejects if that excess exceeds the burst threshold (which is the burst parameter multiplied by 1000). With burst=1, the threshold is 1000 units, so the first request with excess=1000 doesn't get rejected since 1000 is not greater than 1000.\n\nBut the second request at 500ms later has excess=1834, which exceeds 1000 and gets rejected. Subsequent requests continue to be rejected because the state doesn't update when a request is rejected, so the excess value stays high until enough time passes for the decay to bring it back below the threshold.\n\nTo find when the next request can be allowed, I need excess to drop to 0 or below, which happens around 3 seconds after the initial allowed request. Now I'm recalculating the round-robin scenario where requests arrive at different replicas at t=0, 1500, 3000, and 4500ms.\n\nAt t=0, the first request gets through with excess at 1000. At t=1500, the excess has only decayed to 1500, still exceeding the limit, so that request is rejected. By t=3000, the excess should theoretically reach exactly 1000 due to the decay calculation, making it right at the boundary—whether this allows or rejects depends on the exact precision of the computation. At t=4500ms, request 10 gets rejected because the excess reaches 1500, exceeding the limit. So R1 allows requests 1 and 7 but rejects 4 and 10. Now looking at R2's requests at t=500, 2000, and 3500ms—the first one at 500ms passes with the bucket refilled, but the one at 2000ms gets rejected due to excess building up again.\n\nR2 ends up allowing requests 2 and 8 while rejecting request 5. R3 follows the same pattern shifted by 500ms, allowing requests 3 and 9 but rejecting request 6. Across all three rate limiters, I'm seeing 6 requests pass and 4 get rejected, with the distribution being requests 1, 2, 3, 7, 8, 9 allowed and 4, 5, 6, 10 blocked.\n\nThe key insight is that rejected requests don't update the stored state, so the elap