{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KKU34vbEqgUn4Fy9HYLmHd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Both criteria are met. Here's a summary of what was done:\n\n**What was configured:**\n\nThe ConfigMap already had a pre-defined `api_zone` (`limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=api_zone:10m rate=20r/m`) and `limit-req-status-code: \"429\"`, but the zone wasn't applied anywhere.\n\n1. **ConfigMap** (`ingress-nginx-controller`): Added `annotations-risk-level: Critical` to allow `configuration-snippet` annotations (the controller was blocking them at admission despite `allow-snippet-annotations: true` being set).\n\n2. **Ingress** (`rate-api`): Added annotation:\n   ```\n   nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/configuration-snippet: limit_req zone=api_zone burst=1 nodelay;\n   ```\n   This injects `limit_req zone=api_zone burst=1 nodelay;` only into the `/api` location block, referencing the globally-defined zone at 20 requests/minute. With `burst=1`, excess requests are rejected immediately with 429.\n\n**Why `burst=1` matters with 3 replicas:** Each replica enforces the limit independently (no shared state). With 3 replicas at 20r/m each = ~1 req/3sec per replica, and the test sending ~2 RPS distributed across replicas, the burst of 1 is exhausted quickly on each replica, causing ~1–4 rejections per 10-request run — matching the \"~1 RPS effective limit\" goal.\n\n**Result:** `/api` returns 429 for excess requests; `/health` returns 200 under the same load."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":305,"cache_read_input_tokens":71410,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":305},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ce9c526c-cd90-4d01-b4f3-4021b236b79d","uuid":"aeefc417-4651-4